#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:11(title) 
msgid "Installation from Source Code"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:15(primary) 
msgid "installation"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:18(para) 
msgid "This chapter describes the installation of <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> using the source code distribution. (If you are installing a pre-packaged distribution, such as an RPM or Debian package, ignore this chapter and read the packager's instructions instead.)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:30(title) 
msgid "Short Version"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:32(para) 
msgid "<synopsis>\n./configure\ngmake\nsu\ngmake install\nadduser postgres\nmkdir /usr/local/pgsql/data\nchown postgres /usr/local/pgsql/data\nsu - postgres\n/usr/local/pgsql/bin/initdb -D /usr/local/pgsql/data\n/usr/local/pgsql/bin/postgres -D /usr/local/pgsql/data &gt;logfile 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;\n/usr/local/pgsql/bin/createdb test\n/usr/local/pgsql/bin/psql test\n</synopsis> The long version is the rest of this chapter."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:55(title) 
msgid "Requirements"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:57(para) 
msgid "In general, a modern Unix-compatible platform should be able to run <productname>PostgreSQL</productname>. The platforms that had received specific testing at the time of release are listed in <xref linkend=\"supported-platforms\"/> below. In the <filename>doc</filename> subdirectory of the distribution there are several platform-specific <acronym>FAQ</acronym> documents you might wish to consult if you are having trouble."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:73(para) 
msgid "<indexterm><primary>make</primary></indexterm><acronym>GNU</acronym><application>make</application> version 3.80 or newer is required; other <application>make</application> programs or older <acronym>GNU</acronym><application>make</application> versions will <emphasis>not</emphasis> work. <acronym>GNU</acronym><application>make</application> is often installed under the name <filename>gmake</filename>; this document will always refer to it by that name. (On some systems <acronym>GNU</acronym><application>make</application> is the default tool with the name <filename>make</filename>.) To test for <acronym>GNU</acronym><application>make</application> enter: <screen>\n<userinput>gmake --version</userinput>\n</screen>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:93(para) 
msgid "You need an <acronym>ISO</acronym>/<acronym>ANSI</acronym> C compiler (at least C89-compliant). Recent versions of <productname>GCC</productname> are recommendable, but <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> is known to build using a wide variety of compilers from different vendors."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:103(para) 
msgid "<application>tar</application> is required to unpack the source distribution, in addition to either <application>gzip</application> or <application>bzip2</application>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:111(para) 
msgid "<indexterm><primary>readline</primary></indexterm><indexterm><primary>libedit</primary></indexterm> The <acronym>GNU</acronym><productname>Readline</productname> library is used by default. It allows <application>psql</application> (the PostgreSQL command line SQL interpreter) to remember each command you type, and allows you to use arrow keys to recall and edit previous commands. This is very helpful and is strongly recommended. If you don't want to use it then you must specify the <option>--without-readline</option> option to <filename>configure</filename>. As an alternative, you can often use the BSD-licensed <filename>libedit</filename> library, originally developed on <productname>NetBSD</productname>. The <filename>libedit</filename> library is GNU <productname>Readline</productname>-compatible and is used if <filename>libreadline</filename> is not found, or if <option>--with-libedit-preferred</option> is used as an option to <filename>configure</filename>. If you are using a package-based Linux distribution, be aware that you need both the <literal>readline</literal> and <literal>readline-devel</literal> packages, if those are separate in your distribution."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:141(para) 
msgid "<indexterm><primary>zlib</primary></indexterm> The <productname>zlib</productname> compression library is used by default. If you don't want to use it then you must specify the <option>--without-zlib</option> option to <filename>configure</filename>. Using this option disables support for compressed archives in <application>pg_dump</application> and <application>pg_restore</application>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:67(para) 
msgid "The following software packages are required for building <productname>PostgreSQL</productname>: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:164(para) 
msgid "To build the server programming language <application>PL/Perl</application> you need a full <productname>Perl</productname> installation, including the <filename>libperl</filename> library and the header files. Since <application>PL/Perl</application> will be a shared library, the <indexterm><primary>libperl</primary></indexterm><filename>libperl</filename> library must be a shared library also on most platforms. This appears to be the default in recent <productname>Perl</productname> versions, but it was not in earlier versions, and in any case it is the choice of whomever installed Perl at your site. If you intend to make more than incidental use of <application>PL/Perl</application>, you should ensure that the <productname>Perl</productname> installation was built with the <literal>usemultiplicity</literal> option enabled (<literal>perl -V</literal> will show whether this is the case)."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:183(para) 
msgid "If you don't have the shared library but you need one, a message like this will appear during the <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> build to point out this fact: <screen>\n*** Cannot build PL/Perl because libperl is not a shared library.\n*** You might have to rebuild your Perl installation.  Refer to\n*** the documentation for details.\n</screen> (If you don't follow the on-screen output you will merely notice that the <application>PL/Perl</application> library object, <filename>plperl.so</filename> or similar, will not be installed.) If you see this, you will have to rebuild and install <productname>Perl</productname> manually to be able to build <application>PL/Perl</application>. During the configuration process for <productname>Perl</productname>, request a shared library."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:204(para) 
msgid "To build the <application>PL/Python</application> server programming language, you need a <productname>Python</productname> installation with the header files and the <application>distutils</application> module. The minimum required version is <productname>Python</productname> 2.2. <productname>Python 3</productname> is supported if it's version 3.1 or later; but see <xref linkend=\"plpython-python23\"/> when using Python 3."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:217(para) 
msgid "Since <application>PL/Python</application> will be a shared library, the <indexterm><primary>libpython</primary></indexterm><filename>libpython</filename> library must be a shared library also on most platforms. This is not the case in a default <productname>Python</productname> installation. If after building and installing <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> you have a file called <filename>plpython.so</filename> (possibly a different extension), then everything went well. Otherwise you should have seen a notice like this flying by: <screen>\n*** Cannot build PL/Python because libpython is not a shared library.\n*** You might have to rebuild your Python installation.  Refer to\n*** the documentation for details.\n</screen> That means you have to rebuild (part of) your <productname>Python</productname> installation to create this shared library."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:237(para) 
msgid "If you have problems, run <productname>Python</productname> 2.3 or later's configure using the <literal>--enable-shared</literal> flag. On some operating systems you don't have to build a shared library, but you will have to convince the <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> build system of this. Consult the <filename>Makefile</filename> in the <filename>src/pl/plpython</filename> directory for details."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:248(para) 
msgid "To build the <application>PL/Tcl</application> procedural language, you of course need a <productname>Tcl</productname> installation. If you are using a pre-8.4 release of <productname>Tcl</productname>, ensure that it was built without multithreading support."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:258(para) 
msgid "To enable Native Language Support (<acronym>NLS</acronym>), that is, the ability to display a program's messages in a language other than English, you need an implementation of the <application>Gettext</application><acronym>API</acronym>. Some operating systems have this built-in (e.g., <systemitem class=\"osname\">Linux</systemitem>, <systemitem class=\"osname\">NetBSD</systemitem>, <systemitem class=\"osname\">Solaris</systemitem>), for other systems you can download an add-on package from <ulink url=\"http://www.gnu.org/software/gettext/\"/>. If you are using the <application>Gettext</application> implementation in the <acronym>GNU</acronym> C library then you will additionally need the <productname>GNU Gettext</productname> package for some utility programs. For any of the other implementations you will not need it."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:277(para) 
msgid "You need <application>Kerberos</application>, <productname>OpenSSL</productname>, <productname>OpenLDAP</productname>, and/or <application>PAM</application>, if you want to support authentication or encryption using those services."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:157(para) 
msgid "The following packages are optional. They are not required in the default configuration, but they are needed when certain build options are enabled, as explained below: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:294(para) 
msgid "<indexterm><primary>flex</primary></indexterm><indexterm><primary>lex</primary></indexterm><indexterm><primary>bison</primary></indexterm><indexterm><primary>yacc</primary></indexterm> GNU <application>Flex</application> and <application>Bison</application> are needed to build from a Git checkout, or if you changed the actual scanner and parser definition files. If you need them, be sure to get <application>Flex</application> 2.5.31 or later and <application>Bison</application> 1.875 or later. Other <application>lex</application> and <application>yacc</application> programs cannot be used."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:317(para) 
msgid "<indexterm><primary>perl</primary></indexterm><application>Perl</application> 5.8 or later is needed to build from a Git checkout, or if you changed the input files for any of the build steps that use Perl scripts. If building on Windows you will need <application>Perl</application> in any case."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:287(para) 
msgid "If you are building from a <productname>Git</productname> tree instead of using a released source package, or if you want to do server development, you also need the following packages: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:331(para) 
msgid "If you need to get a <acronym>GNU</acronym> package, you can find it at your local <acronym>GNU</acronym> mirror site (see <ulink url=\"http://www.gnu.org/order/ftp.html\"/> for a list) or at <ulink url=\"ftp://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/\"/>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:339(para) 
msgid "Also check that you have sufficient disk space. You will need about 100 MB for the source tree during compilation and about 20 MB for the installation directory. An empty database cluster takes about 35 MB; databases take about five times the amount of space that a flat text file with the same data would take. If you are going to run the regression tests you will temporarily need up to an extra 150 MB. Use the <command>df</command> command to check free disk space."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:353(title) 
msgid "Getting The Source"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:355(para) 
msgid "The <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> &version; sources can be obtained by anonymous FTP from <ulink url=\"ftp://ftp.postgresql.org/pub/source/v&version;/postgresql-&version;.tar.gz\"/>. Other download options can be found on our website: <ulink url=\"http://www.postgresql.org/download/\"/>. After you have obtained the file, unpack it: <screen>\n<userinput>gunzip postgresql-&version;.tar.gz</userinput>\n<userinput>tar xf postgresql-&version;.tar</userinput>\n</screen> This will create a directory <filename>postgresql-&version;</filename> under the current directory with the <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> sources. Change into that directory for the rest of the installation procedure."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:373(para) 
msgid "You can also get the source directly from the version control repository, see <xref linkend=\"sourcerepo\"/>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:381(title) 
msgid "Installation Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:386(title) 
msgid "Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:389(primary) 
msgid "configure"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:392(para) 
msgid "The first step of the installation procedure is to configure the source tree for your system and choose the options you would like. This is done by running the <filename>configure</filename> script. For a default installation simply enter: <screen>\n<userinput>./configure</userinput>\n</screen> This script will run a number of tests to determine values for various system dependent variables and detect any quirks of your operating system, and finally will create several files in the build tree to record what it found. You can also run <filename>configure</filename> in a directory outside the source tree, if you want to keep the build directory separate. This procedure is also called a <indexterm><primary>VPATH</primary></indexterm><firstterm>VPATH</firstterm> build. Here's how: <screen>\n<userinput>mkdir build_dir</userinput>\n<userinput>cd build_dir</userinput>\n<userinput>/path/to/source/tree/configure [options go here]</userinput>\n<userinput>gmake</userinput>\n</screen>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:417(para) 
msgid "The default configuration will build the server and utilities, as well as all client applications and interfaces that require only a C compiler. All files will be installed under <filename>/usr/local/pgsql</filename> by default."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:431(replaceable) 
msgid "PREFIX"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:431(option) 
msgid "--prefix=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:433(para) 
msgid "Install all files under the directory <replaceable>PREFIX</replaceable> instead of <filename>/usr/local/pgsql</filename>. The actual files will be installed into various subdirectories; no files will ever be installed directly into the <replaceable>PREFIX</replaceable> directory."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:441(para) 
msgid "If you have special needs, you can also customize the individual subdirectories with the following options. However, if you leave these with their defaults, the installation will be relocatable, meaning you can move the directory after installation. (The <literal>man</literal> and <literal>doc</literal> locations are not affected by this.)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:450(para) 
msgid "For relocatable installs, you might want to use <filename>configure</filename>'s <literal>--disable-rpath</literal> option. Also, you will need to tell the operating system how to find the shared libraries."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:460(replaceable) 
msgid "EXEC-PREFIX"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:460(option) 
msgid "--exec-prefix=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:462(para) 
msgid "You can install architecture-dependent files under a different prefix, <replaceable>EXEC-PREFIX</replaceable>, than what <replaceable>PREFIX</replaceable> was set to. This can be useful to share architecture-independent files between hosts. If you omit this, then <replaceable>EXEC-PREFIX</replaceable> is set equal to <replaceable>PREFIX</replaceable> and both architecture-dependent and independent files will be installed under the same tree, which is probably what you want."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:476(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:487(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:497(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:508(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:518(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:530(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:542(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:553(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:565(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:577(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:719(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1061(replaceable) 
msgid "DIRECTORY"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:476(option) 
msgid "--bindir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:478(para) 
msgid "Specifies the directory for executable programs. The default is <filename><replaceable>EXEC-PREFIX</replaceable>/bin</filename>, which normally means <filename>/usr/local/pgsql/bin</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:487(option) 
msgid "--sysconfdir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:489(para) 
msgid "Sets the directory for various configuration files, <filename><replaceable>PREFIX</replaceable>/etc</filename> by default."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:497(option) 
msgid "--libdir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:499(para) 
msgid "Sets the location to install libraries and dynamically loadable modules. The default is <filename><replaceable>EXEC-PREFIX</replaceable>/lib</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:508(option) 
msgid "--includedir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:510(para) 
msgid "Sets the directory for installing C and C++ header files. The default is <filename><replaceable>PREFIX</replaceable>/include</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:518(option) 
msgid "--datarootdir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:520(para) 
msgid "Sets the root directory for various types of read-only data files. This only sets the default for some of the following options. The default is <filename><replaceable>PREFIX</replaceable>/share</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:530(option) 
msgid "--datadir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:532(para) 
msgid "Sets the directory for read-only data files used by the installed programs. The default is <filename><replaceable>DATAROOTDIR</replaceable></filename>. Note that this has nothing to do with where your database files will be placed."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:542(option) 
msgid "--localedir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:544(para) 
msgid "Sets the directory for installing locale data, in particular message translation catalog files. The default is <filename><replaceable>DATAROOTDIR</replaceable>/locale</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:553(option) 
msgid "--mandir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:555(para) 
msgid "The man pages that come with <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> will be installed under this directory, in their respective <filename>man<replaceable>x</replaceable></filename> subdirectories. The default is <filename><replaceable>DATAROOTDIR</replaceable>/man</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:565(option) 
msgid "--docdir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:567(para) 
msgid "Sets the root directory for installing documentation files, except <quote>man</quote> pages. This only sets the default for the following options. The default value for this option is <filename><replaceable>DATAROOTDIR</replaceable>/doc/postgresql</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:577(option) 
msgid "--htmldir=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:579(para) 
msgid "The HTML-formatted documentation for <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> will be installed under this directory. The default is <filename><replaceable>DATAROOTDIR</replaceable></filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:590(para) 
msgid "Care has been taken to make it possible to install <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> into shared installation locations (such as <filename>/usr/local/include</filename>) without interfering with the namespace of the rest of the system. First, the string <quote><literal>/postgresql</literal></quote> is automatically appended to <varname>datadir</varname>, <varname>sysconfdir</varname>, and <varname>docdir</varname>, unless the fully expanded directory name already contains the string <quote><literal>postgres</literal></quote> or <quote><literal>pgsql</literal></quote>. For example, if you choose <filename>/usr/local</filename> as prefix, the documentation will be installed in <filename>/usr/local/doc/postgresql</filename>, but if the prefix is <filename>/opt/postgres</filename>, then it will be in <filename>/opt/postgres/doc</filename>. The public C header files of the client interfaces are installed into <varname>includedir</varname> and are namespace-clean. The internal header files and the server header files are installed into private directories under <varname>includedir</varname>. See the documentation of each interface for information about how to access its header files. Finally, a private subdirectory will also be created, if appropriate, under <varname>libdir</varname> for dynamically loadable modules."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:424(para) 
msgid "You can customize the build and installation process by supplying one or more of the following command line options to <filename>configure</filename>: <placeholder-1/><placeholder-2/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:620(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:638(replaceable) 
msgid "DIRECTORIES"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:620(option) 
msgid "--with-includes=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:622(para) 
msgid "<replaceable>DIRECTORIES</replaceable> is a colon-separated list of directories that will be added to the list the compiler searches for header files. If you have optional packages (such as GNU <application>Readline</application>) installed in a non-standard location, you have to use this option and probably also the corresponding <option>--with-libraries</option> option."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:631(para) 
msgid "Example: <literal>--with-includes=/opt/gnu/include:/usr/sup/include</literal>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:638(option) 
msgid "--with-libraries=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:640(para) 
msgid "<replaceable>DIRECTORIES</replaceable> is a colon-separated list of directories to search for libraries. You will probably have to use this option (and the corresponding <option>--with-includes</option> option) if you have packages installed in non-standard locations."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:647(para) 
msgid "Example: <literal>--with-libraries=/opt/gnu/lib:/usr/sup/lib</literal>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:654(replaceable) 
msgid "LANGUAGES"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:654(optional) 
msgid "=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:654(option) 
msgid "--enable-nls<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:656(para) 
msgid "Enables Native Language Support (<acronym>NLS</acronym>), that is, the ability to display a program's messages in a language other than English. <replaceable>LANGUAGES</replaceable> is an optional space-separated list of codes of the languages that you want supported, for example <literal>--enable-nls='de fr'</literal>. (The intersection between your list and the set of actually provided translations will be computed automatically.) If you do not specify a list, then all available translations are installed."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:669(para) 
msgid "To use this option, you will need an implementation of the <application>Gettext</application> API; see above."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:677(replaceable) 
msgid "NUMBER"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:677(option) 
msgid "--with-pgport=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:679(para) 
msgid "Set <replaceable>NUMBER</replaceable> as the default port number for server and clients. The default is 5432. The port can always be changed later on, but if you specify it here then both server and clients will have the same default compiled in, which can be very convenient. Usually the only good reason to select a non-default value is if you intend to run multiple <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> servers on the same machine."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:692(option) 
msgid "--with-perl"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:694(para) 
msgid "Build the <application>PL/Perl</application> server-side language."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:701(option) 
msgid "--with-python"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:703(para) 
msgid "Build the <application>PL/Python</application> server-side language."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:710(option) 
msgid "--with-tcl"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:712(para) 
msgid "Build the <application>PL/Tcl</application> server-side language."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:719(option) 
msgid "--with-tclconfig=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:721(para) 
msgid "Tcl installs the file <filename>tclConfig.sh</filename>, which contains configuration information needed to build modules interfacing to Tcl. This file is normally found automatically at a well-known location, but if you want to use a different version of Tcl you can specify the directory in which to look for it."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:733(option) 
msgid "--with-gssapi"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:735(para) 
msgid "Build with support for GSSAPI authentication. On many systems, the GSSAPI (usually a part of the Kerberos installation) system is not installed in a location that is searched by default (e.g., <filename>/usr/include</filename>, <filename>/usr/lib</filename>), so you must use the options <option>--with-includes</option> and <option>--with-libraries</option> in addition to this option. <filename>configure</filename> will check for the required header files and libraries to make sure that your GSSAPI installation is sufficient before proceeding."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:750(option) 
msgid "--with-krb5"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:752(para) 
msgid "Build with support for Kerberos 5 authentication. On many systems, the Kerberos system is not installed in a location that is searched by default (e.g., <filename>/usr/include</filename>, <filename>/usr/lib</filename>), so you must use the options <option>--with-includes</option> and <option>--with-libraries</option> in addition to this option. <filename>configure</filename> will check for the required header files and libraries to make sure that your Kerberos installation is sufficient before proceeding."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:766(replaceable) 
msgid "NAME"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:766(option) 
msgid "--with-krb-srvnam=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:768(para) 
msgid "The default name of the Kerberos service principal (also used by GSSAPI). <literal>postgres</literal> is the default. There's usually no reason to change this unless you have a Windows environment, in which case it must be set to upper case <literal>POSTGRES</literal>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:781(primary) 
msgid "OpenSSL"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:782(seealso) 
msgid "SSL"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:785(option) 
msgid "--with-openssl"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:787(para) 
msgid "Build with support for <acronym>SSL</acronym> (encrypted) connections. This requires the <productname>OpenSSL</productname> package to be installed. <filename>configure</filename> will check for the required header files and libraries to make sure that your <productname>OpenSSL</productname> installation is sufficient before proceeding."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:799(option) 
msgid "--with-pam"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:801(para) 
msgid "Build with <acronym>PAM</acronym><indexterm><primary>PAM</primary></indexterm> (Pluggable Authentication Modules) support."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:809(option) 
msgid "--with-ldap"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:811(para) 
msgid "Build with <acronym>LDAP</acronym><indexterm><primary>LDAP</primary></indexterm> support for authentication and connection parameter lookup (see <xref linkend=\"libpq-ldap\"/> and <xref linkend=\"auth-ldap\"/> for more information). On Unix, this requires the <productname>OpenLDAP</productname> package to be installed. On Windows, the default <productname>WinLDAP</productname> library is used. <filename>configure</filename> will check for the required header files and libraries to make sure that your <productname>OpenLDAP</productname> installation is sufficient before proceeding."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:827(option) 
msgid "--without-readline"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:829(para) 
msgid "Prevents use of the <application>Readline</application> library (and <application>libedit</application> as well). This option disables command-line editing and history in <application>psql</application>, so it is not recommended."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:839(option) 
msgid "--with-libedit-preferred"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:841(para) 
msgid "Favors the use of the BSD-licensed <application>libedit</application> library rather than GPL-licensed <application>Readline</application>. This option is significant only if you have both libraries installed; the default in that case is to use <application>Readline</application>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:851(option) 
msgid "--with-bonjour"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:853(para) 
msgid "Build with Bonjour support. This requires Bonjour support in your operating system. Recommended on Mac OS X."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:861(option) 
msgid "--with-ossp-uuid"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:863(para) 
msgid "Build components using the <ulink url=\"http://www.ossp.org/pkg/lib/uuid/\">OSSP UUID library</ulink>. Specifically, build the <xref linkend=\"uuid-ossp\"/> module, which provides functions to generate UUIDs.<indexterm><primary>UUID</primary></indexterm>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:876(option) 
msgid "--with-libxml"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:878(para) 
msgid "Build with libxml (enables SQL/XML support). Libxml version 2.6.23 or later is required for this feature."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:883(para) 
msgid "Libxml installs a program <command>xml2-config</command> that can be used to detect the required compiler and linker options. PostgreSQL will use it automatically if found. To specify a libxml installation at an unusual location, you can either set the environment variable <envar>XML2_CONFIG</envar> to point to the <command>xml2-config</command> program belonging to the installation, or use the options <option>--with-includes</option> and <option>--with-libraries</option>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:899(option) 
msgid "--with-libxslt"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:901(para) 
msgid "Use libxslt when building the <xref linkend=\"xml2\"/> module. <application>xml2</application> relies on this library to perform XSL transformations of XML."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:912(option) 
msgid "--disable-integer-datetimes"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:914(para) 
msgid "Disable support for 64-bit integer storage for timestamps and intervals, and store datetime values as floating-point numbers instead. Floating-point datetime storage was the default in <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> releases prior to 8.4, but it is now deprecated, because it does not support microsecond precision for the full range of <type>timestamp</type> values. However, integer-based datetime storage requires a 64-bit integer type. Therefore, this option can be used when no such type is available, or for compatibility with applications written for prior versions of <productname>PostgreSQL</productname>. See <xref linkend=\"datatype-datetime\"/> for more information."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:934(option) 
msgid "--disable-float4-byval"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:936(para) 
msgid "Disable passing float4 values <quote>by value</quote>, causing them to be passed <quote>by reference</quote> instead. This option costs performance, but may be needed for compatibility with old user-defined functions that are written in C and use the <quote>version 0</quote> calling convention. A better long-term solution is to update any such functions to use the <quote>version 1</quote> calling convention."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:949(option) 
msgid "--disable-float8-byval"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:951(para) 
msgid "Disable passing float8 values <quote>by value</quote>, causing them to be passed <quote>by reference</quote> instead. This option costs performance, but may be needed for compatibility with old user-defined functions that are written in C and use the <quote>version 0</quote> calling convention. A better long-term solution is to update any such functions to use the <quote>version 1</quote> calling convention. Note that this option affects not only float8, but also int8 and some related types such as timestamp. On 32-bit platforms, <option>--disable-float8-byval</option> is the default and it is not allowed to select <option>--enable-float8-byval</option>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:968(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1005(replaceable) 
msgid "SEGSIZE"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:968(option) 
msgid "--with-segsize=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:970(para) 
msgid "Set the <firstterm>segment size</firstterm>, in gigabytes. Large tables are divided into multiple operating-system files, each of size equal to the segment size. This avoids problems with file size limits that exist on many platforms. The default segment size, 1 gigabyte, is safe on all supported platforms. If your operating system has <quote>largefile</quote> support (which most do, nowadays), you can use a larger segment size. This can be helpful to reduce the number of file descriptors consumed when working with very large tables. But be careful not to select a value larger than is supported by your platform and the file systems you intend to use. Other tools you might wish to use, such as <application>tar</application>, could also set limits on the usable file size. It is recommended, though not absolutely required, that this value be a power of 2. Note that changing this value requires an initdb."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:991(replaceable) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1019(replaceable) 
msgid "BLOCKSIZE"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:991(option) 
msgid "--with-blocksize=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:993(para) 
msgid "Set the <firstterm>block size</firstterm>, in kilobytes. This is the unit of storage and I/O within tables. The default, 8 kilobytes, is suitable for most situations; but other values may be useful in special cases. The value must be a power of 2 between 1 and 32 (kilobytes). Note that changing this value requires an initdb."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1005(option) 
msgid "--with-wal-segsize=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1007(para) 
msgid "Set the <firstterm>WAL segment size</firstterm>, in megabytes. This is the size of each individual file in the WAL log. It may be useful to adjust this size to control the granularity of WAL log shipping. The default size is 16 megabytes. The value must be a power of 2 between 1 and 64 (megabytes). Note that changing this value requires an initdb."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1019(option) 
msgid "--with-wal-blocksize=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1021(para) 
msgid "Set the <firstterm>WAL block size</firstterm>, in kilobytes. This is the unit of storage and I/O within the WAL log. The default, 8 kilobytes, is suitable for most situations; but other values may be useful in special cases. The value must be a power of 2 between 1 and 64 (kilobytes). Note that changing this value requires an initdb."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1033(option) 
msgid "--disable-spinlocks"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1035(para) 
msgid "Allow the build to succeed even if <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> has no CPU spinlock support for the platform. The lack of spinlock support will result in poor performance; therefore, this option should only be used if the build aborts and informs you that the platform lacks spinlock support. If this option is required to build <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> on your platform, please report the problem to the <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> developers."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1049(option) 
msgid "--disable-thread-safety"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1051(para) 
msgid "Disable the thread-safety of client libraries. This prevents concurrent threads in <application>libpq</application> and <application>ECPG</application> programs from safely controlling their private connection handles."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1061(option) 
msgid "--with-system-tzdata=<placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1063(primary) 
msgid "time zone data"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1066(para) 
msgid "<productname>PostgreSQL</productname> includes its own time zone database, which it requires for date and time operations. This time zone database is in fact compatible with the <quote>zoneinfo</quote> time zone database provided by many operating systems such as FreeBSD, Linux, and Solaris, so it would be redundant to install it again. When this option is used, the system-supplied time zone database in <replaceable>DIRECTORY</replaceable> is used instead of the one included in the PostgreSQL source distribution. <replaceable>DIRECTORY</replaceable> must be specified as an absolute path. <filename>/usr/share/zoneinfo</filename> is a likely directory on some operating systems. Note that the installation routine will not detect mismatching or erroneous time zone data. If you use this option, you are advised to run the regression tests to verify that the time zone data you have pointed to works correctly with <productname>PostgreSQL</productname>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1084(primary) 
msgid "cross compilation"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1086(para) 
msgid "This option is mainly aimed at binary package distributors who know their target operating system well. The main advantage of using this option is that the PostgreSQL package won't need to be upgraded whenever any of the many local daylight-saving time rules change. Another advantage is that PostgreSQL can be cross-compiled more straightforwardly if the time zone database files do not need to be built during the installation."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1100(option) 
msgid "--without-zlib"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1102(para) 
msgid "<indexterm><primary>zlib</primary></indexterm> Prevents use of the <application>Zlib</application> library. This disables support for compressed archives in <application>pg_dump</application> and <application>pg_restore</application>. This option is only intended for those rare systems where this library is not available."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1116(option) 
msgid "--enable-debug"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1118(para) 
msgid "Compiles all programs and libraries with debugging symbols. This means that you can run the programs in a debugger to analyze problems. This enlarges the size of the installed executables considerably, and on non-GCC compilers it usually also disables compiler optimization, causing slowdowns. However, having the symbols available is extremely helpful for dealing with any problems that might arise. Currently, this option is recommended for production installations only if you use GCC. But you should always have it on if you are doing development work or running a beta version."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1134(option) 
msgid "--enable-coverage"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1136(para) 
msgid "If using GCC, all programs and libraries are compiled with code coverage testing instrumentation. When run, they generate files in the build directory with code coverage metrics. See <xref linkend=\"regress-coverage\"/> for more information. This option is for use only with GCC and when doing development work."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1149(option) 
msgid "--enable-profiling"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1151(para) 
msgid "If using GCC, all programs and libraries are compiled so they can be profiled. On backend exit, a subdirectory will be created that contains the <filename>gmon.out</filename> file for use in profiling. This option is for use only with GCC and when doing development work."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1161(option) 
msgid "--enable-cassert"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1163(para) 
msgid "Enables <firstterm>assertion</firstterm> checks in the server, which test for many <quote>cannot happen</quote> conditions. This is invaluable for code development purposes, but the tests can slow down the server significantly. Also, having the tests turned on won't necessarily enhance the stability of your server! The assertion checks are not categorized for severity, and so what might be a relatively harmless bug will still lead to server restarts if it triggers an assertion failure. This option is not recommended for production use, but you should have it on for development work or when running a beta version."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1180(option) 
msgid "--enable-depend"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1182(para) 
msgid "Enables automatic dependency tracking. With this option, the makefiles are set up so that all affected object files will be rebuilt when any header file is changed. This is useful if you are doing development work, but is just wasted overhead if you intend only to compile once and install. At present, this option only works with GCC."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1194(option) 
msgid "--enable-dtrace"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1196(para) 
msgid "<indexterm><primary>DTrace</primary></indexterm> Compiles <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> with support for the dynamic tracing tool DTrace. See <xref linkend=\"dynamic-trace\"/> for more information."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1206(para) 
msgid "To point to the <command>dtrace</command> program, the environment variable <envar>DTRACE</envar> can be set. This will often be necessary because <command>dtrace</command> is typically installed under <filename>/usr/sbin</filename>, which might not be in the path."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1214(para) 
msgid "Extra command-line options for the <command>dtrace</command> program can be specified in the environment variable <envar>DTRACEFLAGS</envar>. On Solaris, to include DTrace support in a 64-bit binary, you must specify <literal>DTRACEFLAGS=\"-64\"</literal> to configure. For example, using the GCC compiler: <screen>\n./configure CC='gcc -m64' --enable-dtrace DTRACEFLAGS='-64' ...\n</screen> Using Sun's compiler: <screen>\n./configure CC='/opt/SUNWspro/bin/cc -xtarget=native64' --enable-dtrace DTRACEFLAGS='-64' ...\n</screen>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1235(para) 
msgid "If you prefer a C compiler different from the one <filename>configure</filename> picks, you can set the environment variable <envar>CC</envar> to the program of your choice. By default, <filename>configure</filename> will pick <filename>gcc</filename> if available, else the platform's default (usually <filename>cc</filename>). Similarly, you can override the default compiler flags if needed with the <envar>CFLAGS</envar> variable."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:1245(para) 
msgid "You can specify environment variables on the <filename>configure</filename> command line, for example: <screen>\n<userinput>./configure CC=/opt/bin/gcc CFLAGS='-O2 -pipe'</userinput>\n</screen>"
msgstr ""

