msgid "Start <command>cygserver</command> for shared memory support. To do this, enter the command <literal>/usr/sbin/cygserver &amp;</literal>. This program needs to be running anytime you start the PostgreSQL server or initialize a database cluster (<command>initdb</command>). The default <command>cygserver</command> configuration may need to be changed (e.g., increase <symbol>SEMMNS</symbol>) to prevent PostgreSQL from failing due to a lack of system resources."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2224(para) 
msgid "Building might fail on some systems where a locale other than C is in use. To fix this, set the locale to C by doing <command>export LANG=C.utf8</command> before building, and then setting it back to the previous setting, after you have installed PostgreSQL."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2241(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nmake MAX_CONNECTIONS=5 check\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2234(para) 
msgid "The parallel regression tests (<literal>make check</literal>) can generate spurious regression test failures due to overflowing the <function>listen()</function> backlog queue which causes connection refused errors or hangs. You can limit the number of connections using the make variable <varname>MAX_CONNECTIONS</varname> thus: <placeholder-1/> (On some systems you can have up to about 10 simultaneous connections)."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2167(para) 
msgid "When building from source, proceed according to the normal installation procedure (i.e., <literal>./configure; make</literal>; etc.), noting the following-Cygwin specific differences: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2251(para) 
msgid "It is possible to install <command>cygserver</command> and the PostgreSQL server as Windows NT services. For information on how to do this, please refer to the <filename>README</filename> document included with the PostgreSQL binary package on Cygwin. It is installed in the directory <filename>/usr/share/doc/Cygwin</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2262(title) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2265(primary) 
msgid "HP-UX"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2269(para) 
msgid "PostgreSQL 7.3+ should work on Series 700/800 PA-RISC machines running HP-UX 10.X or 11.X, given appropriate system patch levels and build tools. At least one developer routinely tests on HP-UX 10.20, and we have reports of successful installations on HP-UX 11.00 and 11.11."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2277(para) 
msgid "Aside from the PostgreSQL source distribution, you will need GNU make (HP's make will not do), and either GCC or HP's full ANSI C compiler. If you intend to build from Git sources rather than a distribution tarball, you will also need Flex (GNU lex) and Bison (GNU yacc). We also recommend making sure you are fairly up-to-date on HP patches. At a minimum, if you are building 64 bit binaries on on HP-UX 11.11 you may need PHSS_30966 (11.11) or a successor patch otherwise <command>initdb</command> may hang: <literallayout>\nPHSS_30966  s700_800 ld(1) and linker tools cumulative patch\n</literallayout> On general principles you should be current on libc and ld/dld patches, as well as compiler patches if you are using HP's C compiler. See HP's support sites such as <ulink url=\"http://itrc.hp.com\"/> and <ulink url=\"ftp://us-ffs.external.hp.com/\"/> for free copies of their latest patches."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2298(para) 
msgid "If you are building on a PA-RISC 2.0 machine and want to have 64-bit binaries using GCC, you must use GCC 64-bit version. GCC binaries for HP-UX PA-RISC and Itanium are available from <ulink url=\"http://www.hp.com/go/gcc\"/>. Don't forget to get and install binutils at the same time."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2306(para) 
msgid "If you are building on a PA-RISC 2.0 machine and want the compiled binaries to run on PA-RISC 1.1 machines you will need to specify <option>+DAportable</option> in <envar>CFLAGS</envar>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2312(para) 
msgid "If you are building on a HP-UX Itanium machine, you will need the latest HP ANSI C compiler with its dependent patch or successor patches: <literallayout>\nPHSS_30848  s700_800 HP C Compiler (A.05.57)\nPHSS_30849  s700_800 u2comp/be/plugin library Patch\n</literallayout>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2326(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\n./configure CC=cc\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2330(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\n./configure CC=gcc\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2322(para) 
msgid "If you have both HP's C compiler and GCC's, then you might want to explicitly select the compiler to use when you run <command>configure</command>: <placeholder-1/> for HP's C compiler, or <placeholder-2/> for GCC. If you omit this setting, then configure will pick <command>gcc</command> if it has a choice."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2337(para) 
msgid "The default install target location is <filename>/usr/local/pgsql</filename>, which you might want to change to something under <filename>/opt</filename>. If so, use the <option>--prefix</option> switch to <command>configure</command>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2345(para) 
msgid "In the regression tests, there might be some low-order-digit differences in the geometry tests, which vary depending on which compiler and math library versions you use. Any other error is cause for suspicion."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2354(title) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2357(primary) 
msgid "IRIX"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2361(para) 
msgid "PostgreSQL has been reported to run successfully on MIPS r8000, r10000 (both ip25 and ip27) and r12000(ip35) processors, running IRIX 6.5.5m, 6.5.12, 6.5.13, and 6.5.26 with MIPSPro compilers version 7.30, 7.3.1.2m, 7.3, and 7.4.4m."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2368(para) 
msgid "You will need the MIPSPro full ANSI C compiler. There are problems trying to build with GCC. It is a known GCC bug (not fixed as of version 3.0) related to using functions that return certain kinds of structures. This bug affects functions like <function>inet_ntoa</function>, <function>inet_lnaof</function>, <function>inet_netof</function>, <function>inet_makeaddr</function>, and <function>semctl</function>. It is supposed to be fixed by forcing code to link those functions with libgcc, but this has not been tested yet."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2379(para) 
msgid "It is known that version 7.4.1m of the MIPSPro compiler generates incorrect code. The symptom is <quote>invalid primary checkpoint record</quote> when trying to start the database.) Version 7.4.4m is OK; the status of intermediate versions is uncertain."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2386(para) 
msgid "There may be a compilation problem like the following: <screen>\ncc-1020 cc: ERROR File = pqcomm.c, Line = 427\n  The identifier \"TCP_NODELAY\" is undefined.\n\n                if (setsockopt(port-&gt;sock, IPPROTO_TCP, TCP_NODELAY,\n</screen> Some versions include TCP definitions in <filename>sys/xti.h</filename>, so it is necessary to add <literal>#include &lt;sys/xti.h&gt;</literal> in <filename>src/backend/libpq/pqcomm.c</filename> and in <filename>src/interfaces/libpq/fe-connect.c</filename>. If you encounter this, please let us know so we can develop a proper fix."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2402(para) 
msgid "In the regression tests, there might be some low-order-digit differences in the geometry tests, depending on which FPU are you using. Any other error is cause for suspicion."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2410(title) 
msgid "MinGW/Native Windows"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2413(primary) 
msgid "MinGW"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2417(para) 
msgid "PostgreSQL for Windows can be built using MinGW, a Unix-like build environment for Microsoft operating systems, or using Microsoft's <productname>Visual C++</productname> compiler suite. The MinGW build variant uses the normal build system described in this chapter; the Visual C++ build works completely differently and is described in <xref linkend=\"install-windows\"/>. It is a fully native build and uses no additional software like MinGW. A ready-made installer is available on the main PostgreSQL web site."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2429(para) 
msgid "The native Windows port requires a 32 or 64-bit version of Windows 2000 or later. Earlier operating systems do not have sufficient infrastructure (but Cygwin may be used on those). MinGW, the Unix-like build tools, and MSYS, a collection of Unix tools required to run shell scripts like <command>configure</command>, can be downloaded from <ulink url=\"http://www.mingw.org/\"/>. Neither is required to run the resulting binaries; they are needed only for creating the binaries."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2441(para) 
msgid "To build 64 bit binaries using MinGW, install the 64 bit tool set from <ulink url=\"http://mingw-w64.sourceforge.net/\"/>, put its bin directory in the <envar>PATH</envar>, and run <command>configure</command> with the <command>--host=x86_64-w64-mingw</command> option."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2449(para) 
msgid "After you have everything installed, it is suggested that you run <application>psql</application> under <command>CMD.EXE</command>, as the MSYS console has buffering issues."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2457(title) 
msgid "Collecting Crash Dumps on Windows"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2459(para) 
msgid "If PostgreSQL on Windows crashes, it has the ability to generate <productname>minidumps</productname> that can be used to track down the cause for the crash, similar to core dumps on Unix. These dumps can be read using the <productname>Windows Debugger Tools</productname> or using <productname>Visual Studio</productname>. To enable the generation of dumps on Windows, create a subdirectory named <filename>crashdumps</filename> inside the cluster data directory. The dumps will then be written into this directory with a unique name based on the identifier of the crashing process and the current time of the crash."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2474(title) 
msgid "SCO OpenServer and SCO UnixWare"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2477(primary) 
msgid "SCO"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2482(primary) 
msgid "UnixWare"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2486(para) 
msgid "PostgreSQL can be built on SCO UnixWare 7 and SCO OpenServer 5. On OpenServer, you can use either the OpenServer Development Kit or the Universal Development Kit. However, some tweaking may be needed, as described below."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2494(title) 
msgid "Skunkware"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2496(para) 
msgid "You should locate your copy of the SCO Skunkware CD. The Skunkware CD is included with UnixWare 7 and current versions of OpenServer 5. Skunkware includes ready-to-install versions of many popular programs that are available on the Internet. For example, gzip, gunzip, GNU Make, Flex, and Bison are all included. For UnixWare 7.1, this CD is now labeled \"Open License Software Supplement\". If you do not have this CD, the software on it is available from <ulink url=\"http://www.sco.com/skunkware/\"/>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2508(para) 
msgid "Skunkware has different versions for UnixWare and OpenServer. Make sure you install the correct version for your operating system, except as noted below."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2514(para) 
msgid "On UnixWare 7.1.3 and beyond, the GCC compiler is included on the UDK CD as is GNU Make."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2521(title) 
msgid "GNU Make"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2523(para) 
msgid "You need to use the GNU Make program, which is on the Skunkware CD. By default, it installs as <filename>/usr/local/bin/make</filename>. To avoid confusion with the SCO <filename>make</filename> program, you may want to rename GNU <filename>make</filename> to <filename>gmake</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2531(para) 
msgid "As of UnixWare 7.1.3 and above, the GNU Make program is is the OSTK portion of the UDK CD, and is in <filename>/usr/gnu/bin/gmake</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2539(title) 
msgid "Readline"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2541(para) 
msgid "The Readline library is on the Skunkware CD. But it is not included on the UnixWare 7.1 Skunkware CD. If you have the UnixWare 7.0.0 or 7.0.1 Skunkware CDs, you can install it from there. Otherwise, try <ulink url=\"http://www.sco.com/skunkware/\"/>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2555(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\n./configure --with-libraries=/usr/local/lib --with-includes=/usr/local/include\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2549(para) 
msgid "By default, Readline installs into <filename>/usr/local/lib</filename> and <filename>/usr/local/include</filename>. However, the PostgreSQL <command>configure</command> program will not find it there without help. If you installed Readline, then use the following options to <command>configure</command>: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2562(title) 
msgid "Using the UDK on OpenServer"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2568(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\n./configure --with-libraries=/udk/usr/lib --with-includes=/udk/usr/include\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2572(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\n./configure --with-libraries=\"/udk/usr/lib /usr/local/lib\" --with-includes=\"/udk/usr/include /usr/local/include\"\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2564(para) 
msgid "If you are using the new Universal Development Kit (UDK) compiler on OpenServer, you need to specify the locations of the UDK libraries: <placeholder-1/> Putting these together with the Readline options from above: <placeholder-2/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2579(title) 
msgid "Reading the PostgreSQL Man Pages"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2588(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nMANPATH=/usr/lib/scohelp/%L/man:/usr/dt/man:/usr/man:/usr/share/man:scohelp:/usr/local/man:/usr/local/pgsql/man\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2581(para) 
msgid "By default, the PostgreSQL man pages are installed into <filename>/usr/local/pgsql/man</filename>. By default, UnixWare does not look there for man pages. To be able to read them you need to modify the <varname>MANPATH</varname> variable in <filename>/etc/default/man</filename>, for example: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2593(para) 
msgid "On OpenServer, some extra research needs to be invested to make the man pages usable, because the man system is a bit different from other platforms. Currently, PostgreSQL will not install them at all."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2602(title) 
msgid "C99 Issues with the 7.1.1b Feature Supplement"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2604(para) 
msgid "For compilers earlier than the one released with OpenUNIX 8.0.0 (UnixWare 7.1.2), including the 7.1.1b Feature Supplement, you may need to specify <option>-Xb</option> in <varname>CFLAGS</varname> or the <varname>CC</varname> environment variable. The indication of this is an error in compiling <filename>tuplesort.c</filename> referencing inline functions. Apparently there was a change in the 7.1.2(8.0.0) compiler and beyond."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2617(title) 
msgid "Threading on UnixWare"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2619(para) 
msgid "For threading, you<emphasis>must</emphasis> use <option>-Kpthread</option> on <emphasis>all</emphasis> libpq-using programs. libpq uses <function>pthread_*</function> calls, which are only available with the <option>-Kpthread</option>/<option>-Kthread</option> flag."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2630(title) /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2633(primary) 
msgid "Solaris"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2637(para) 
msgid "PostgreSQL is well-supported on Solaris. The more up to date your operating system, the fewer issues you will experience; details below."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2643(para) 
msgid "Note that PostgreSQL is bundled with Solaris 10 (from update 2). Official packages are also available on <ulink url=\"http://pgfoundry.org/projects/solarispackages/\"/>. Packages for older Solaris versions (8, 9) you can be obtained from <ulink url=\"http://www.sunfreeware.com/\"/> or <ulink url=\"http://www.blastwave.org/\"/>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2653(title) 
msgid "Required Tools"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2655(para) 
msgid "You can build with either GCC or Sun's compiler suite. For better code optimization, Sun's compiler is strongly recommended on the SPARC architecture. We have heard reports of problems when using GCC 2.95.1; GCC 2.95.3 or later is recommended. If you are using Sun's compiler, be careful not to select <filename>/usr/ucb/cc</filename>; use <filename>/opt/SUNWspro/bin/cc</filename>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2665(para) 
msgid "You can download Sun Studio from <ulink url=\"http://developers.sun.com/sunstudio/downloads/\"/>. Many of GNU tools are integrated into Solaris 10, or they are present on the Solaris companion CD. If you like packages for older version of Solaris, you can find these tools at <ulink url=\"http://www.sunfreeware.com\"/> or <ulink url=\"http://www.blastwave.org\"/>. If you prefer sources, look at <ulink url=\"http://www.gnu.org/order/ftp.html\"/>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2679(title) 
msgid "Problems with OpenSSL"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2685(filename) 
msgid "src/backend/libpq/crypt.c"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2686(filename) 
msgid "src/backend/libpq/password.c"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2687(filename) 
msgid "src/interfaces/libpq/fe-auth.c"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2688(filename) 
msgid "src/interfaces/libpq/fe-connect.c"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2681(para) 
msgid "When you build PostgreSQL with OpenSSL support you might get compilation errors in the following files: <placeholder-1/> This is because of a namespace conflict between the standard <filename>/usr/include/crypt.h</filename> header and the header files provided by OpenSSL."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2696(para) 
msgid "Upgrading your OpenSSL installation to version 0.9.6a fixes this problem. Solaris 9 and above has a newer version of OpenSSL."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2703(title) 
msgid "configure Complains About a Failed Test Program"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2712(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nconfigure ... LDFLAGS=\"-R /usr/sfw/lib:/opt/sfw/lib:/usr/local/lib\"\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2705(para) 
msgid "If <command>configure</command> complains about a failed test program, this is probably a case of the run-time linker being unable to find some library, probably libz, libreadline or some other non-standard library such as libssl. To point it to the right location, set the <envar>LDFLAGS</envar> environment variable on the <command>configure</command> command line, e.g., <placeholder-1/> See the <citerefentry><refentrytitle>ld</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry> man page for more information."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2722(title) 
msgid "64-bit Build Sometimes Crashes"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2733(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nLIBOBJS =\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2737(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nLIBOBJS = snprintf.o\n"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2724(para) 
msgid "On Solaris 7 and older, the 64-bit version of libc has a buggy <function>vsnprintf</function> routine, which leads to erratic core dumps in PostgreSQL. The simplest known workaround is to force PostgreSQL to use its own version of <function>vsnprintf</function> rather than the library copy. To do this, after you run <command>configure</command> edit a file produced by <command>configure</command>: In <filename>src/Makefile.global</filename>, change the line <placeholder-1/> to read <placeholder-2/> (There might be other files already listed in this variable. Order does not matter.) Then build as usual."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2746(title) 
msgid "Compiling for Optimal Performance"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2748(para) 
msgid "On the SPARC architecture, Sun Studio is strongly recommended for compilation. Try using the <option>-xO5</option> optimization flag to generate significantly faster binaries. Do not use any flags that modify behavior of floating-point operations and <varname>errno</varname> processing (e.g., <option>-fast</option>). These flags could raise some nonstandard PostgreSQL behavior for example in the date/time computing."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2759(para) 
msgid "If you do not have a reason to use 64-bit binaries on SPARC, prefer the 32-bit version. The 64-bit operations are slower and 64-bit binaries are slower than the 32-bit variants. And on other hand, 32-bit code on the AMD64 CPU family is not native, and that is why 32-bit code is significant slower on this CPU family."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2768(para) 
msgid "Some tricks for tuning PostgreSQL and Solaris for performance can be found at <ulink url=\"http://www.sun.com/servers/coolthreads/tnb/applications_postgresql.jsp\"/>. This article is primary focused on T2000 platform, but many of the recommendations are also useful on other hardware with Solaris."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2779(title) 
msgid "Using DTrace for Tracing PostgreSQL"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2781(para) 
msgid "Yes, using DTrace is possible. See <xref linkend=\"dynamic-trace\"/> for further information. You can also find more information in this article: <ulink url=\"http://blogs.sun.com/robertlor/entry/user_level_dtrace_probes_in\"/>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-ivSD/installation.xml:2788(para) 
msgid "If you see the linking of the <command>postgres</command> executable abort with an error message like: <screen>\nUndefined                       first referenced\n symbol                             in file\nAbortTransaction                    utils/probes.o\nCommitTransaction                   utils/probes.o\nld: fatal: Symbol referencing errors. No output written to postgres\ncollect2: ld returned 1 exit status\ngmake: *** [postgres] Error 1\n</screen> your DTrace installation is too old to handle probes in static functions. You need Solaris 10u4 or newer."
msgstr ""

